<!-- Section 1: Executive Summary -->
<section data-section="executive-summary" class="proposal-section hidden">
  <div class="proposal-content">
    <h2 class="text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-bold text-[#1B2A4A] mb-6">1. Executive Summary</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      Cloud9 needs a tool that turns SharePoint data into interactive architecture visualisations.
      Consultants and their clients should be able to explore application landscapes, filter by any
      dimension, trace integration dependencies, and export what they see into slide decks and
      client-ready documents, without maintaining manual diagrams that go stale the moment they're drawn.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      The tool also represents a commercial opportunity. Each client deployment costs approximately $64
      per month in Azure infrastructure. Cloud9 determines the pricing model, with the margin per client
      being the difference between the chosen price point and the infrastructure cost. The full business
      case, including revenue projections and investment payback analysis, is presented in Section 2.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      <strong>We propose building this tool in 8 weeks</strong> with a two-person senior development
      team, starting with a focused one-week discovery, four weeks of development, one week of UAT, and
      two weeks of hypercare support.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1B2A4A] mt-8 mb-4">Three Architectural Decisions</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
      Three architectural decisions define this proposal:
    </p>

    <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2 text-[#2D2D2D]">
      <li>
        <strong>Single-tenant deployment, not multi-tenant.</strong> Each Cloud9 client gets their
        own isolated instance &mdash; their own database, their own application, their own URL. This
        is materially more cost-effective for Cloud9 to run at launch than the enterprise multi-tenant
        architecture described in the RFP. It provides stronger data isolation by default (physical
        separation, not logical), and simplifies build time and complexity. The architecture is designed
        for multi-tenant migration when client count reaches a single-tenant cost threshold (~18 clients),
        and that migration can be executed with no client impact.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>SharePoint stays as the source of truth.</strong> The tool reads from SharePoint via
        daily sync with a manual refresh option. In the MLP phase, a &ldquo;check-out&rdquo; model
        lets users create working copies for target-state planning without touching the synced data.
        This eliminates issues relating to &lsquo;source-of-truth&rsquo;.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Feasibility drives phase allocation.</strong> We have evaluated the proposed feature
        sequencing against Desirability, Viability, and Feasibility. Features that can deliver high
        value quickly have been moved forward. This means Degree of Hops (the feature that demonstrates
        impact analysis to architects) and PDF export both move into the MVP, alongside PNG export.
      </li>
    </ol>

